<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-hol-1">
  <title>Definition of Higher-Order Linear ODEs</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Which of the following is a fourth‑order <em>linear</em> differential equation?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>y^{(4)} + p(x)y'' + q(x)y' + r(x)y = 0</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. An <m>n</m>th‑order linear ODE may be written as  
          <m>A_n(x)y^{(n)} + \dots + A_0(x)y = F(x)</m>, with no nonlinear functions of <m>y</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y^{(4)} + (y')^{2} = 0</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Not linear: <m>(y')^{2}</m> is nonlinear.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y'' + p(x)y = 0</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>This is linear but only second‑order, not higher‑order.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-hol-2">
  <title>Superposition Principle</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      For the homogeneous equation <m>L[y] = 0</m>, where <m>L</m> is a linear differential operator
      of order <m>n</m>, which statement is true?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>If <m>y_1,\dots,y_k</m> are solutions, then any linear combination of them is also a solution.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Linear operators satisfy  
          <m>L(c_1y_1 + \dots + c_ky_k) = c_1L(y_1) + \dots + c_kL(y_k)</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The product <m>y_1 y_2</m> is always a solution.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—products do not preserve linearity.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Only <m>y_1</m> can be used; other solutions are irrelevant.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—higher‑order ODEs require multiple independent solutions.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-hol-3">
  <title>Characteristic Polynomial for a 3rd-Order ODE</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the characteristic polynomial for the ODE  
      <m>y''' - 2y'' + y' = 0</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>r^{3} - 2r^{2} + r = 0</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Substituting <m>y=e^{rx}</m> gives <m>r^3 - 2r^2 + r = 0</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>r^{2} - 2r + 1 = 0</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>This is only quadratic; the ODE is third‑order.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>r^{3} + r^{2} - 2r = 0</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>The sign of the <m>r^2</m> term is incorrect.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-hol-4">
  <title>Independent Solutions and Order</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      How many linearly independent solutions are needed to describe the general solution of an 
      <m>n</m>th‑order linear homogeneous ODE?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>Exactly <m>n</m> linearly independent solutions.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. An <m>n</m>th‑order linear ODE requires <m>n</m> fundamental solutions to span the
          solution space.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Only one solution is needed.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this works only for first‑order equations.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Infinitely many solutions must be listed individually.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect—only <m>n</m> independent ones are required.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-hol-5">
  <title>Solving a 3rd-Order ODE</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve the homogeneous ODE  
      <m>y''' - 3y'' + 3y' = 0</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>y = C_1 + C_2 x + C_3 x^{2}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The characteristic polynomial is  
          <m>r^3 - 3r^2 + 3r = r(r-1)^2</m>,  
          giving roots <m>0</m> and <m>1</m> (double).  
          Solutions are <m>e^{0x}=1</m>, <m>e^{x}</m>, and <m>xe^{x}</m>; rewritten in polynomial form,
          this yields <m>C_1 + C_2 x + C_3 x^{2}</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = C_1 e^{x} + C_2 e^{-x} + C_3 e^{2x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Those roots do not satisfy the characteristic polynomial.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = C_1 e^{x} + C_2 x e^{x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Missing the third independent solution.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="higherorder-1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the general solution to  
      <m>y''' + 2y'' - y' - 2y = 0.</m>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Write the characteristic equation:
    </p>

    <me>
      r^{3} + 2r^{2} - r - 2 = 0.
    </me>

    <p>
      Factor by grouping:
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow> r^{2}(r+2) - 1(r+2) \amp = (r^{2} - 1)(r+2) </mrow>
                     <mrow> \amp    = (r-1)(r+1)(r+2). </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>
      Thus the roots are <m>r=1</m>, <m>r=-1</m>, and <m>r=-2</m>.  
      The general solution is:
    </p>

    <me>
      y(x) = C_{1} e^{x} + C_{2} e^{-x} + C_{3} e^{-2x}.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="higherorder-2">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the general solution to  
      <m>y^{(iv)} - y''' + 2y' = 0.</m>  
      <em>Hint:</em> The characteristic polynomial factors as  
      <m>r(r+1)(r^{2} - 2r + 2) = 0.</m>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Using the factorization:
    </p>

    <me>
      r(r+1)(r^{2} - 2r + 2) = 0.
    </me>

    <p>
      The real roots are <m>r=0</m> and <m>r=-1</m>.  
      The quadratic factor gives:
    </p>

    <me>
      r^{2} - 2r + 2 = 0
      \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
      r = 1 \pm i.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus the solution pieces are:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><m>e^{0x} = 1</m></li>
      <li><m>e^{-x}</m></li>
      <li><m>e^{x}\cos x</m>, <m>e^{x}\sin x</m> (from <m>1 \pm i</m>)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Therefore the general solution is:
    </p>

    <me>
       y(x)
      = C_{1}
        + C_{2} e^{-x}
        + C_{3} e^{x} \cos x
        + C_{4} e^{x} \sin x.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="higherorder-3">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the general solution to  
      <m>y^{(v)} + 18y''' + 81y' = 0.</m>  
      <em>Hint:</em> The characteristic polynomial factors as  
      <m>r(r^{2} + 9)^{2} = 0.</m>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      From the factorization:
    </p>

    <me>
      r(r^{2}+9)^{2} = 0,
    </me>

    <p>
      the roots are:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><m>r = 0</m></li>
      <li><m>r = 3i</m> (double root)</li>
      <li><m>r = -3i</m> (double root)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      For <m>r=0</m>, the solution term is <m>1</m>.  
      For the repeated complex roots <m>\pm 3i</m>, the general solution includes:
    </p>

    <me>
      \cos 3x,\quad \sin 3x,\quad x\cos 3x,\quad x\sin 3x.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore the general solution is:
    </p>

    <me>
      y(x)
      = C_{1}
        + C_{2}\cos(3x)
        + C_{3}\sin(3x)
        + C_{4}x\cos(3x)
        + C_{5}x\sin(3x).
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="sec23-wronskian-1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the functions
      <m>y_{1}(x) = e^{x}</m>,  
      <m>y_{2}(x) = e^{2x}</m>, and  
      <m>y_{3}(x) = e^{3x}</m>.
      Compute their Wronskian
      <m>W(y_{1},y_{2},y_{3})(x)</m>.  
      What does the result tell you about linear independence?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      The Wronskian of three functions is
    </p>

    <me>
      W =
      \begin{vmatrix}
        y_1 \amp y_2 \amp y_3 \\
        y_1' \amp y_2' \amp y_3' \\
        y_1'' \amp y_2'' \amp y_3''
      \end{vmatrix}
      =
      \begin{vmatrix}
        e^{x} \amp e^{2x} \amp e^{3x} \\
        e^{x} \amp 2e^{2x} \amp 3e^{3x} \\
        e^{x} \amp 4e^{2x} \amp 9e^{3x}
      \end{vmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Factor out <m>e^{x}, e^{2x}, e^{3x}</m> from each column:
    </p>

    <me>
      W = e^{x} e^{2x} e^{3x}
      \begin{vmatrix}
        1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
        1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
        1 \amp 4 \amp 9
      \end{vmatrix}
      = e^{6x}
      \begin{vmatrix}
        1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
        1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
        1 \amp 4 \amp 9
      \end{vmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Compute the 3×3 determinant:
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow> \begin{vmatrix}
        1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
        1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
        1 \amp 4 \amp 9
      \end{vmatrix}
      \amp =
      1(2\cdot 9 - 3\cdot 4)
      -1(1\cdot 9 - 3\cdot 1)
      +1(1\cdot 4 - 2\cdot 1) </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = (18 - 12) - (9 - 3) + (4 - 2) </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = 6 - 6 + 2 </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = 2. </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>
      Therefore:
    </p>

    <me>
      W(y_{1},y_{2},y_{3})(x) = 2 e^{6x}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Since <m>W(x) \neq 0</m> for all <m>x</m>, the functions are
      <strong>linearly independent</strong> on every interval.  
      They therefore form a fundamental set of solutions for a third‑order linear homogeneous ODE.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="sec23-wronskian-2">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let
      <m>y_{1}(x) = x</m>,  
      <m>y_{2}(x) = x^{2}</m>,  
      <m>y_{3}(x) = x^{3}</m>.  
      Compute the Wronskian <m>W(y_{1},y_{2},y_{3})(x)</m> and determine whether the functions are
      linearly independent.  
      Are they valid as a fundamental solution set for a third‑order linear homogeneous ODE?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Compute the Wronskian:
    </p>

    <me>
      W =
      \begin{vmatrix}
        x \amp x^{2} \amp x^{3} \\
        1 \amp 2x \amp 3x^{2} \\
        0 \amp 2 \amp 6x
      \end{vmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>Expand along the first row:</p>

    <me>
      W
      =
      x
      \begin{vmatrix}
        2x \amp 3x^{2} \\
        2 \amp 6x
      \end{vmatrix}
      - x^{2}
      \begin{vmatrix}
        1 \amp 3x^{2} \\
        0 \amp 6x
      \end{vmatrix}
      + x^{3}
      \begin{vmatrix}
        1 \amp 2x \\
        0 \amp 2
      \end{vmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>Compute each 2×2 determinant:</p>

    <md>
      <mrow> x[(2x)(6x) - (3x^{2})(2)]
        - x^{2}[6x]
        + x^{3}[2]
      \amp =
      x(12x^{2} - 6x^{2})
        - 6x^{3}
        + 2x^{3} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =
      x(6x^{2})
        - 4x^{3} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =
      6x^{3} - 4x^{3} </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =
      2x^{3}. </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>
      Thus:
    </p>

    <me>
      W(y_1,y_2,y_3)(x) = 2 x^{3}.
    </me>

    <p>
      The Wronskian is zero only at <m>x=0</m>, but nonzero for <m>x \neq 0</m>.  
      Therefore, the functions are <strong>linearly independent</strong> on any interval not containing 0  
      (e.g., <m>(0,\infty)</m> or <m>(-\infty,0)</m>).
    </p>

    <p>
      Hence they form a valid fundamental solution set for a third‑order homogeneous linear ODE  
      on any such interval.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

      <section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives23">
        <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
      Apply the Wronskian to determine whether a given set of functions forms a <em>fundamental solution set</em> on an interval.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Analyze how computational challenges increase when moving from second‑order equations to 
      higher‑order equations and compare available solution methods.
            </p>
          </li>

